      "npcs": [
        {
          "id": "ferrywoman_brack",
          "x": 20,
          "y": 7,
          "name": "Ferrywoman Brack",
          "dialogue": [
            {
              "when": { "relapsed": ["the_font", true] },
              "lines": [
                "Punt won't go out today. There's light under the water again — Font-light, moving with a purpose.",
                "Somebody woke what you put to sleep. Get down the causeway before it remembers how many of us live on its shore."
              ]
            },
            {
              "when": { "verdict": ["the_font", "Purge"] },
              "lines": [
                "Water's never been this clear. You can see all the way down now — the vats, the old town, the bones of both.",
                "Nothing swims across my bow anymore. I used to curse the splashing. Turns out the splashing was the mere being alive."
              ]
            },
            {
              "when": { "verdict": ["the_font", "Reseed"] },
              "lines": [
                "Shoals came back to the shallows this spring. Real ones, wild ones, no seams in them anywhere.",
                "First time in my life the wake behind the punt has company. I sing to it. Don't you dare tell the anglers."
              ]
            },
            {
              "when": { "verdict": ["the_font", "Bind"] },
              "lines": [
                "They say the Font pours for you now. That you ask it for living things and it says yes.",
                "The old world asked it for things too. The lakes are clear enough to read the answer, if you ever want to look down."
              ]
            },
            {
              "lines": [
                "Mind the water. It's clear as glass and that's the trick of it — clear just means you can see what the old world sank, not that it's gone.",
                "Vats, hull-sections, whole caged shipments that never got unloaded. The mere keeps it all polished and waiting.",
                "West along the shore is Saltwick. East is the drowned causeway, and the Font at the end of it. Only one of those is a kindness."
              ],
              "set_flags": ["mirrormere_met_brack"]
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "id": "angler_theo",
          "x": 7,
          "y": 12,
          "name": "Angler Theo",
          "lines": [
            "Three rules of the mere: fish the reeds, never fish the deep glass, and if your float goes down slow — cut the line.",
            "Slow means something's tasting it. Things that taste first were built careful, and careful things were built for war.",
            "Caught a Lutrin pup in my keep-net last month. It handed me back my own sinkers, one by one, like an apology."
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
